# How Much Does YouTube Pay For 1 Million Views?

Reaching one million views is a major milestone for any creator.

But how much does YouTube actually pay for 1 million views?

The answer depends primarily on RPM.

## Estimated Earnings For 1 Million Views

| RPM | Earnings |
| --- | -------- |
| $1  | $1,000   |
| $3  | $3,000   |
| $5  | $5,000   |
| $10 | $10,000  |
| $20 | $20,000  |

As you can see, the same number of views can generate vastly different revenue depending on niche and audience.

## What Determines RPM?

Several factors influence RPM:

* Viewer location
* Content niche
* Watch time
* Ad inventory demand
* Seasonality

## High-Paying Niches

The highest RPM categories often include:

* Personal Finance
* Investing
* Insurance
* Software
* Business
* Real Estate

Creators in these niches can sometimes exceed $20 RPM.

## Lower-Paying Niches

Some niches typically have lower RPM:

* Entertainment
* Gaming
* Memes
* General Vlogs

These channels often rely on larger audiences to generate substantial income.

## Beyond Ad Revenue

Many creators earn significantly more through:

* Affiliate marketing
* Sponsorships
* Digital products
* Memberships
* Courses

For many successful channels, ads represent only a portion of total income.

## Final Thoughts

One million views can generate anywhere from $1,000 to more than $20,000 depending on RPM.

Understanding RPM is essential for maximizing YouTube revenue and building a sustainable creator business.
